(788, 'Autoritratto di Antonio Canova', 'Gesso - mm. 890x470x390@it', 0, 0, ''),
(789, 'Church of Saint Anthony the Abbot in Rieti', 'The church of Saint Anthony the Abbot, after having been annexed to another architectural complex is now unfortunately closed to the public.The building was built and designed by Vignola. The facade, in brick and travertine, testifies to his devotion to models by Michelangelo, as well as a chiaroscuro and a plastic conception of the architectural surface that is in fact enriched by a giant order of pilasters, arches, and Ionic capitals. Its implementation is still incomplete, as seen by the absence of marble cladding and the presence instead of the holes that were used to support the scaffoldings. The building is the only one in Rieti that was made on the basis of the dictates laid down by the Council of Trent, who, for religious architecture, provided that churches had to have a single nave, be barrel vaulted and have a broad apse with a spectacularly raised altar.All things considered, the resulting structure remains difficult to read, accentuated by the fact that the church, after years of complete lack of maintenance, became deconsecrated, which may in turn erase the collective memory of the community that has grown up around it.', 42.4033, 12.8644, ''),
(772, 'Tondo con il giudizio di Paride dalla camera di ricevimento dell''Alcova Torlonia', 'tempera su tela - mm. 1240 (diam.)@it', 0, 0, ''),
(773, 'Ritratto di John Staples', 'olio su tela - mm. 2640x1980@it', 0, 0, ''),
(774, 'Torre Truglia - Sperlonga', 'Torre Truglia (Truglia Tower) was built in 1532 on the foundations of a pre-existing Roman watchtower situated on the bare stone cliffs on the point of the promontory where the town of Sperlonga stands. Two years later it was devastated by the hordes of Kaireddin Barbarossa and rebuilt in 1611 only to be destroyed again in 1623 by the Turks. It was rebuilt during the following century together with Nibbio and Capovento towers to become an integral part of the coastal defence system that was instrumental along the entire coastline. From 1870 to 1969 it was used by the Italian Finance Police (Guardia di Finanza).  ', 41.2546, 13.434, ''),
